			    STPJS 187</div>
  <p class="std">We are glad to hear of the organization of the different quorums in this city, and hope that their
  organization will be attended to in every stake and branch of the Church, for the Almighty is a lover
  of order<span class="footRef">1</span> and good government.</p>
  <p class="std">From the faith and enterprise of the Saints generally, we feel greatly encouraged and cheerfully
  attend to the important duties devolving upon us,<span class="footRef">2</span> knowing that we not only have the approval of
  Heaven, but also that our efforts for the establishment of Zion and the spread of truth, are cheerfully
  seconded by the thousands of Israel.<span class="footRef">3</span></p>
  <p class="std">In conclusion we would say, brethren, be faithful, let your love and moderation be known unto
  all men;<span class="footRef">4</span> be patient, be mindful<span class="footRef">5</span> to observe all the commandments<span class="footRef">6</span> of your Heavenly Father, and
  the God of all grace<span class="footRef">7</span> shall bless you. Even so. Amen.<span class="footRef">8</span>&mdash;DHC 4:336–339.</p>
  <div class="signatureBlock">
    <p class="signatureLine">JOSEPH SMITH, President</p>
    <p class="signatureLine">ROBERT B. THOMPSON, Clerk.</p>
  </div>
  <p class="wideEllipse">* * *</p>

  <div class="topic">The Prophet&rsquo;s Discourse on Gospel Principles</div>
  <p class="std">At 10 o&rsquo;clock a.m. [May 16, 1841], a large concourse of the Saints assembled on the meeting
  ground, and were addressed by President Joseph Smith, who spoke at considerable length.</p>
  <div class="topic">The Doctrine of Agency</div>
  <p class="std">He commenced his observations by remarking that the kindness of our Heavenly Father called
  for our heartfelt gratitude. He then observed that Satan was generally blamed for the evils which we
  did, but if he was the cause of all our wickedness, men could not be condemned. The devil could not
  compel mankind to do evil; all was voluntary.<span class="footRef">9</span> Those who resisted the Spirit of God,<span class="footRef">10</span> would be
  liable to be led into temptation,<span class="footRef">11</span> and then the association of heaven would be withdrawn<span class="footRef">12</span> from
  those who refused to be made<span class="footRef">13</span> partakers of such great glory.<span class="footRef">14</span> God would not exert any compulsory
  means,<span class="footRef">15</span> and the devil could not; and such ideas as were entertained [on these subjects] by many
  were absurd. The creature was made subject to vanity, not willingly, but Christ subjected the same
  in hope<span class="footRef">16</span>&mdash;all are subjected to vanity while they travel through the crooked paths<span class="footRef">17</span> and difficulties
  which surrounded them. Where is the man that is free from vanity?<span class="footRef">18</span> None ever were perfect but
  Jesus;<span class="footRef">19</span></p>
